	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b>here's a raid healing idea to kick around</b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">problem: raids are often over-dependent on clerics.  the other priests have neither the healing power nor efficiency to keep up.  healing added to the other priests would be to the detriment of the cleric in non-raiding situations.<br />
<br />
idea: use the charm mechanic of "effect gets stronger in certain situations" to apply to all classes' current healing ability as a focus-like effect in raid situations.    this  effect could impact mana cost, casting times, and raw healing output in various ways.<br />
<br />
one implementation idea: add a slot to all the charms and offer via an npc an augment to go into it.  this augment "improves heals as more people are in the raid". <br />
<br />
so for example, with 18 people in the raid, all heals, direct and over time,  might go up 5 percent in total efficacy, and at 72 it might go up 20 percent (numbers just pulled out of a hat).  so in a full raid, the idea is that shaman heals become druid-like, druid heals become cleric-like, and cleric heals become obscene.<br />
<br />
upsides:<br />
<br />
*) fits in with current game mechanics<br />
*) healers won't have to do anything differently than they were doing before.  no memming of different spells or getting used to  a new game dynamic.<br />
*) no heal balancing between classes needs to be done, as all are affected equally<br />
*) lets paladins and other hybrids with heals in on the fun for free (and makes them a possible healing impact player as well)<br />
<br />
downsides:<br />
<br />
*) will probably make some raid events even more trivial, especially if the raid decides to bring along the extra clerics anyway.  (although as an evil idea, the charm could also factor in number of healers into its power....)<br />
*) clerics are already healing gods.  it's hard to judge what would happen were we made ubergods<br />
<br />
i'm sure it needs work, what do you think of the general idea?  any show-stoppers?</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
